**State:** $dp[i][j]$ = LCS length of \texttt{text1[:i]} and \texttt{text2[:j]}.

**Recurrence:** \[dp[i][j] = \begin{cases}dp[i-1][j-1]+1&\text{if }\texttt{text1}[i-1]=\texttt{text2}[j-1] \\ \max(dp[i-1][j],\;dp[i][j-1])&\text{otherwise}\end{cases}\]

**Base cases:** $dp[0][j]=dp[i][0]=0$ (empty prefix).

\begin{lstlisting}
def longestCommonSubsequence(text1: str, text2: str) -> int:
    m, n = len(text1), len(text2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if text1[i-1] == text2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])
    return dp[m][n]
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(mn)$ time, $O(mn)$ space; reduce to $O(\min(m,n))$ by keeping only the previous row.

**Key insight:** LCS is the foundation for many other 2-D string problems. Characters match $\to$ extend diagonal; otherwise take the better of “skip one from either string”.

**State:** $dp[i][j]$ = edit distance between \texttt{word1[:i]} and \texttt{word2[:j]}.

**Recurrence:** \[dp[i][j] = \begin{cases}dp[i-1][j-1]&\text{if }w_{1}[i-1]=w_{2}[j-1] \\ 1 + \min(dp[i-1][j],\;dp[i][j-1],\;dp[i-1][j-1])&\text{otherwise (delete, insert, replace)}\end{cases}\]

**Base cases:** $dp[i][0]=i$ (delete all), $dp[0][j]=j$ (insert all).

\begin{lstlisting}
def minDistance(word1: str, word2: str) -> int:
    m, n = len(word1), len(word2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(m + 1): dp[i][0] = i   # delete i chars
    for j in range(n + 1): dp[0][j] = j   # insert j chars
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if word1[i-1] == word2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]
            else:
                dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j],    # delete from word1
                                   dp[i][j-1],    # insert into word1
                                   dp[i-1][j-1])  # replace
    return dp[m][n]
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(mn)$ time, $O(mn)$ space.

**Visualise the recurrence:** Think of a grid where moving *down* = delete, moving *right* = insert, and moving *diagonally* = replace (or free if chars match).

**State:** $dp[i][j]$ = \texttt{True} iff \texttt{s3[:i+j]} can be formed by interleaving \texttt{s1[:i]} and \texttt{s2[:j]}.

**Recurrence:** \[dp[i][j] = \bigl(dp[i-1][j] \wedge s_{1}[i-1]=s_{3}[i+j-1]\bigr) \;\vee\; \bigl(dp[i][j-1] \wedge s_{2}[j-1]=s_{3}[i+j-1]\bigr)\]

\begin{lstlisting}
def isInterleave(s1: str, s2: str, s3: str) -> bool:
    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)
    if m + n != len(s3): return False
    dp = [[False] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    dp[0][0] = True
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        dp[i][0] = dp[i-1][0] and s1[i-1] == s3[i-1]
    for j in range(1, n + 1):
        dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-1] and s2[j-1] == s3[j-1]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            dp[i][j] = (dp[i-1][j] and s1[i-1] == s3[i+j-1]) or \
                       (dp[i][j-1] and s2[j-1] == s3[i+j-1])
    return dp[m][n]
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(mn)$ time, $O(mn)$ space (reducible to $O(n)$ with a 1-D rolling array).

**Key insight:** At each cell $(i,j)$, we consumed $i$ chars from \texttt{s1} and $j$ from \texttt{s2}, so we've consumed $i+j$ chars of \texttt{s3}. The next char of \texttt{s3} is at index $i+j-1$.

**State machine:** At each day, you are in one of three states: \begin{itemize}\item **held**: currently holding a stock

\item **sold**: just sold today (must cooldown tomorrow)

\item **rest**: in cooldown or idle (can buy tomorrow)\end{itemize}

**Transitions:** \[\texttt{held}= \max(\texttt{held},\;\texttt{rest}- \texttt{price})\] \[\texttt{sold}= \texttt{held}+ \texttt{price}\] \[\texttt{rest}= \max(\texttt{rest},\;\texttt{sold})\]

\begin{lstlisting}
def maxProfit(prices: list[int]) -> int:
    held = float('-inf')   # max profit while holding
    sold = 0               # max profit just after selling
    rest = 0               # max profit while resting/idle
    for price in prices:
        held, sold, rest = (max(held, rest - price),  # buy or hold
                            held + price,             # sell today
                            max(rest, sold))          # cooldown or stay idle
    return max(sold, rest)
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(n)$ time, $O(1)$ space.

**Key insight:** State machine DP explicitly names each “mode” and writes transitions between them. The initial \texttt{held = -inf} prevents buying before any day exists. This pattern generalises to LC 121–188 (stock problems with various constraints: at most $k$ transactions, transaction fee, etc.).

**State:** $dp[i][j]$ = \texttt{True} iff \texttt{p[:j]} matches \texttt{s[:i]}.

**Recurrence:** \begin{itemize}\item If $p[j-1]$ is a literal or \texttt{.}: match single char. $dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]$ if $p[j-1]$ matches $s[i-1]$.

\item If $p[j-1]$ is \texttt{*}: consider two sub-cases: \begin{itemize}\item Use *zero* copies of $p[j-2]$: $dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2]$.

\item Use *one or more* copies: valid only if $p[j-2]$ matches $s[i-1]$. Then $dp[i][j] \mathrel{|}= dp[i-1][j]$ (“consume one more char of \texttt{s}”).\end{itemize}\end{itemize}

\begin{lstlisting}
def isMatch(s: str, p: str) -> bool:
    m, n = len(s), len(p)
    dp = [[False] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    dp[0][0] = True
    # Handle patterns like a*, a*b*, a*b*c* matching empty string
    for j in range(2, n + 1):
        if p[j-1] == '*':
            dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if p[j-1] == '*':
                dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2]                    # zero occurrences
                if p[j-2] == '.' or p[j-2] == s[i-1]:
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i][j] or dp[i-1][j]    # one+ occurrences
            elif p[j-1] == '.' or p[j-1] == s[i-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]
    return dp[m][n]
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(mn)$ time, $O(mn)$ space.

**Key insight:** The \texttt{*} case has two branches: zero uses (skip two pattern chars) or one-or-more uses (consume one source char). The “one or more” branch uses $dp[i-1][j]$ (not $dp[i-1][j-2]$) because the \texttt{*} remains active.

**State:** $dp[i][j]$ = number of ways \texttt{t[:j]} appears as a subsequence of \texttt{s[:i]}.

**Recurrence:** \begin{itemize}\item Always: $dp[i][j] \mathrel{+}= dp[i-1][j]$ (skip $s[i-1]$: all ways using only $s[:i-1]$).

\item If $s[i-1]=t[j-1]$: additionally $dp[i][j] \mathrel{+}= dp[i-1][j-1]$ (match $s[i-1]$ with $t[j-1]$).\end{itemize}

**Base cases:** $dp[i][0]=1$ for all $i$ (empty \texttt{t} is always a subsequence).

\begin{lstlisting}
def numDistinct(s: str, t: str) -> int:
    m, n = len(s), len(t)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]
    for i in range(m + 1):
        dp[i][0] = 1          # empty t is always a subsequence
    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j]              # skip s[i-1]
            if s[i-1] == t[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] += dp[i-1][j-1]       # match s[i-1] with t[j-1]
    return dp[m][n]
\end{lstlisting}

**Complexity:** $O(mn)$ time, $O(mn)$ space (reducible to $O(n)$).

**Key insight:** At each cell, you always have the option to *skip* the current character of \texttt{s}. If it matches, you also have the option to *use* it. Summing both options counts all distinct ways.
